<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
<worksheet xml:id="act-1">
  <title>Activity 1</title>

  <!-- Optional introduction -->
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Instructions:</alert> Write solutions to each of the following problems in the space provided. You are encouraged to work in groups, but also encouraged to use your own words to express your ideas. 
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <!-- Exercises start here. -->
  <page>
        <exercise workspace="1in">
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    Go to the <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_named_differential_equations"/>Wikipedia entry entitled "List of Named Differential Equations". For each of the following categories, chose and write down a differential equation that stands out to you and one listed application for it. Identify the equations order, then state whether it is ordinary or partial. If it is ordinary, determine whether it is linear. 
                </p>
            </introduction>

            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Math
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>

            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Physics
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>

            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Engineering
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>

            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Chemistry
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>

            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Biology and medicine
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>

            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Economics and finance
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </exercise>
    </page>

    <page>
        <exercise workspace="2in">
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    For each of the following, write an initial value problem to model the scenario.
                </p>
            </introduction>

            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Population growth:</alert> The culture was seeded with 500 bacteria, whose population <m>p</m> growth rate at time <m>t</m> grew proportionally to its population.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>

            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Harmonic Oscillator:</alert> A mass <m>m</m> kg is attached to a spring and hung from the ceiling. The spring is stretched by <m>x_0</m> meters from its equilibrium position and is let go, setting the system in (bouncy, springy) motion. Let <m>x(t)</m> denote the spring's position <m>x</m> at time <m>t</m>. 
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </exercise>
    </page>
    
    <page>
        <exercise workspace="3in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <alert>Solar Collector:</alert> A solar collector is shaped like the solid generated by revolving the curve <m>C</m> about the <m>x</m>-axis. Its purpose is to reflect all light light rays parallel to its axis of symmetry to the same point (the origin). The Law of reflection tells us that the angle of incedence <m>\delta</m> and reflection <m>\gamma</m> are equal. Write a differential equation that describes the shape of <m>C</m>. 

                    

                    <!-- <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                        <definition> a=1 </definition>
                        <definition> b=1 </definition>
                        <definition> C(x,y) = (-x+sqrt(x*x+y*y))/y </definition>
                        <coordinates bbox="[-5,0,5,5]">
                            <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" />
                            <graph function="C"/>
                            <tangent-line function="C" point="(a,b)"/>
                            <point p="(a,C(a,b))">
                                <m>(a,b)</m>
                            </point>
                        </coordinates>
                    </diagram> -->
                </p>
            </statement>

            <hint>
                <p>
                   Try showing the the angle <m>\beta</m> the reflected ray makes with respect to the <m>x</m>-axis is exactly twice the angle <m>\alpha></m> the tangent line to <m>C</m> makes with respect to the <m>x</m> axis. 
                </p>
            </hint>
        </exercise>
    </page>

</worksheet>
